      "readmeDetail": "### 3. Use Partial Orthogonalization Instead Of Always Flattening All Singular Values\n\n- Rank: 3\n- Motivation: Full polar updates amplify small singular directions as much as large ones, which may help rare directions but may also amplify noise.\n- Mechanism: Interpolate between raw momentum and polar update, or use a singular-value transform that raises small directions without making all directions equal.\n- Expected benefit: 125 to 250 steps by allowing higher LR or better validation stability.\n- Concrete experiment: Test updates of the form `alpha * Ortho(H) + (1 - alpha) * H / rms(H)` with `alpha` in `{0.5, 0.75, 0.9, 1.0}`, and test polynomial targets that converge to a band rather than exactly one. Keep per-matrix RMS constant to isolate direction effects.\n- Expected failure mode: The main benefit of Muon may be full singular-value flattening; partial versions may collapse back toward ordinary momentum.\n- Confidence: 0.58\n- Expected step gain: 180\n\nDetailed explanation: Muon's story is compelling, but \"all singular directions should receive equal scale\" is stronger than \"rare directions are under-served.\" The latter could be true while the former is too aggressive. A partial polar update would test whether the speedup comes from full spectral sign behavior or simply from reducing the condition number of the update.",
