      "readmeDetail": "### 5. Schedule Muon Momentum Across Training\n\n- Rank: 5\n- Motivation: `mu=0.95` may be too sluggish early and too stale late.\n- Mechanism: Lower momentum during the chaotic first phase can respond faster to feature formation, while higher momentum later can reduce noise as validation loss approaches the threshold.\n- Expected benefit: 80 to 180 steps.\n- Concrete experiment: Compare fixed `mu` values `{0.9, 0.925, 0.95, 0.975}` against schedules such as `0.9 -> 0.97` over training or `0.97 -> 0.93` during cooldown. Keep LR fixed first, then retune LR for the best momentum schedule.\n- Expected failure mode: Momentum and orthogonalization may interact nonlinearly; changing `mu` may require enough LR retuning that the signal is expensive to isolate.\n- Confidence: 0.53\n- Expected step gain: 125\n\nDetailed explanation: Since Muon orthogonalizes after momentum, the buffer defines the singular directions that get equalized. Bad momentum is not just a magnitude issue; it rotates the update subspace. A schedule could let Muon use fresher directions early and cleaner directions late.",
      "rowContext": "## Method Summary\n\nRow 1 uses Muon for the hidden 2D transformer weights and AdamW for the parameters that Muon is not intended to handle well. The model is a 12-layer, width-768 GPT with RMSNorm, separate Q, K, V projections, rotary attention, ReLU-squared MLPs, zero-initialized projection parameters, and a fixed FineWeb training/validation setup. The optimizer split is the core research object:\n\n- AdamW handles the embedding matrix, output projection weight, and all parameters with fewer than 2 dimensions. Its groups use learning rates `0.3` for the embedding, `1/320` for the output head, and `0.01` for scalar/vector parameters, with betas `(0.8, 0.95)`, `eps=1e-10`, and no weight decay.\n- Muon handles all 2D block parameters in `model.blocks`, with learning rate `0.02`, weight decay `0.01`, momentum `mu=0.95`, and Nesterov-style momentum before orthogonalization.\n- The learning-rate schedule is constant for the first 30% of training, then linearly decays to zero across the remaining 70%.\n\nThe Muon update first forms a momentum-smoothed matrix update, then replaces that matrix by an approximately semi-orthogonal matrix using Newton-Schulz iteration. In plain terms, it keeps the update's left and right singular directions but flattens the singular values toward one, so low-energy directions in the raw gradient or momentum are not crushed by a few dominant directions.\n\n## Research Taste Diagnosis\n\nThe promising part is that Muon is a high-leverage structural change: it attacks matrix update geometry directly while preserving the cheapness and simplicity of momentum. The auxiliary Adam split also shows good taste: do not force a matrix polar update onto embeddings, output layers, gains, and biases just because a new optimizer is exciting.\n\nThe fragile part is that all visible evidence is a single run. A one-seed record that finishes just below the target can be improved by real optimizer insight, but it can also be moved by noise, schedule luck, or validation-set fluctuation. The benchmark design rewards step count, so a method with slightly worse final loss variance but better mean crossing time could look good or bad depending on the seed. Future work should separate robust mean improvement from record-chasing.\n\nThe undertuned part is the uniformity. Muon is applied to all hidden 2D matrices with one learning rate, one momentum, one decay, one orthogonalization strength, and one shape scaling formula. Attention Q/K/V, attention output projection, MLP expansion, and MLP projection are not the same optimization problem. The biggest near-term gains probably come from respecting those differences while keeping the optimizer simple.",
