      "matches": [],
      "readmeDetail": "## Revealed Row\n\n| # | Steps to 3.28 | Evidence | Description | Date | Log | Contributors |\n| - | - | - | - | - | - | - |\n| 2 | 5625 | 3.2790 (n=1)Ⓧ | [AdamW](https://arxiv.org/abs/1711.05101) lr=0.0015 wd=0.1 betas=(0.9, 0.95) warmup_steps=250 (note: this is most likely undertuned) | 2026/04/26 | [log](results/a63a68d1-24aa-4a22-af9a-224e43209ea4.txt) | [@kellerjordan0](https://x.com/kellerjordan0) |\n\n## Method Summary\n\nRow 2 is an AdamW baseline for the hidden block matrices that row 1 optimized with Muon. The architecture and most training structure remain very close to row 1: 12 layers, width 768, RMSNorm, separate Q/K/V projections, rotary attention, ReLU-squared MLPs, projection parameters initialized to zero, the same FineWeb batch size, and validation every 125 steps.\n\nThe optimizer split is:\n\n- Auxiliary AdamW for embedding, output head, and non-2D parameters, with the same nominal learning rates as row 1: embedding `0.3`, output head `1/320`, scalar/vector params `0.01`, betas `(0.8, 0.95)`, `eps=1e-10`, no weight decay.\n- Block AdamW for all 2D hidden block parameters, with learning rate `0.0015`, weight decay `0.10`, betas `(0.9, 0.95)`, `eps=1e-10`.\n- Warmup of 250 steps is stored on every optimizer group in the log, so both auxiliary and block groups appear to receive the same multiplicative warmup.\n- The same broad schedule shape is used after warmup: constant until 30% progress, then linear decay over the remaining 70%.\n\nThe Muon class is present in the logged script, but it is not used by the row 2 optimizer list. This row is therefore best read as a pure AdamW replacement for the hidden matrix portion of the row 1 Muon recipe, not as a hybrid.\n\n## Evidence Readout\n\n- Steps to `3.28`: 5625 reported.\n- Validation evidence: final validation loss `3.27903`; rounded row evidence `3.2790`.\n- Seed count: `n=1`.\n- Date: 2026/04/26.\n- Caveats: one seed; the row itself says likely undertuned; no AdamW tuning grid is revealed; the method is worse than the already-revealed Muon row in step efficiency; no direct ablation isolates warmup, weight decay, betas, or block LR.\n\nSelected validation points:\n\n| Step | Val Loss |\n| -: | -: |\n| 0 | 10.82584 |\n| 125 | 6.18993 |\n| 250 | 5.07445 |\n| 500 | 4.15174 |\n| 1000 | 3.77288 |\n| 2000 | 3.55221 |\n| 3000 | 3.44107 |\n| 4000 | 3.36230 |\n| 5000 | 3.30259 |\n| 5500 | 3.28145 |\n| 5625 | 3.27903 |\n\nThe curve is smooth and still descending at the end. The target is crossed only just before the configured final step, so schedule and LR tuning likely matter a lot.\n\n## Research Taste Diagnosis\n\nThis row is valuable because it makes the baseline concrete. It is not a frontier improvement over row 1, but it teaches a taste lesson: a strong optimizer claim needs a serious conventional baseline. The row also shows why \"AdamW vs Muon\" is not a single binary comparison. AdamW could be undertuned by block LR, weight decay, betas, warmup, schedule, or parameter grouping.\n\nThe most suspicious choice is the single hidden-block AdamW group. The same LR/WD/betas are applied to attention and MLP matrices even though their gradient statistics and roles differ. The second suspicious choice is the schedule: a 250-step warmup and a 70% cooldown may be reasonable, but there is no evidence that it is optimal for AdamW's slower early trajectory.\n\nThe result also sharpens row 1's lesson. Muon likely gives something that plain AdamW lacks for hidden matrices, but a fair conclusion requires making AdamW much less undertuned. A future researcher should both try to beat the AdamW row directly and use it to diagnose what Muon's matrix geometry contributes.",
