      "readmeDetail": "### 11. Project MuonH Updates Onto The Sphere Tangent Space Before Stepping\n\n- Rank: 11\n- Motivation: The current hyperball step moves in the full update direction and then renormalizes, which may waste update components that point radially.\n- Mechanism: Remove the radial component of the Muon update relative to the current matrix before the step, then take a normalized tangent step and retract to the sphere.\n- Expected benefit: More of the update budget goes into angular movement, potentially improving efficiency under fixed-radius constraints.\n- Concrete experiment: Implement `U_tangent = U - <U, W> W / ||W||^2`, then use the same norm-scaled MuonH retraction and compare with row 5.\n- Expected failure mode: The radial component may encode useful curvature information even if the final radius is fixed.\n- Confidence: medium-low\n- Expected step gain: 0 to 50\n\nDetailed explanation:\n\nOnce the parameter lives on a sphere, the natural optimization object is the tangent-space direction. Row 5's projection may already approximate this sufficiently, but making it explicit is a clean geometry experiment.",
