      "readmeDetail": "### 5. Combine MuonH-Style Radius Targets With Decay Instead Of Projection\n\n- Rank: 5\n- Motivation: High-WD Muon is robust, and MuonH's per-module radii are strong priors.\n- Mechanism: Use decoupled WD or a radial penalty to pull each matrix toward a target radius rather than projecting exactly.\n- Expected benefit: Get smoother radial control than hard hyperball while using better radius targets than default WD alone.\n- Concrete experiment: Choose row 5-style per-module target radii, run Muon directions, and add radial correction toward those targets with several strengths.\n- Expected failure mode: The hybrid may inherit the complexity of MuonH without matching its stability.\n- Confidence: medium\n- Expected step gain: 0 to 75\n\nDetailed explanation:\n\nThis is a middle path between row 5 and row 6. It treats row 5 radii as targets and row 6 WD as a soft control mechanism.",
