      "readmeDetail": "## Revealed Row\n\n| 7 | 3325 | 3.2752 (n=1)✓ | [Muon²](https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.09967) with aux Adam, lr=.10 wd=.0125 β₂=.95 ε=1e-10 | 2026/04/29 | [log](results/20260501_muonsq/bb903816-ea27-4f5f-8028-c963d38c6a7f.txt) | [PR](https://github.com/KellerJordan/modded-nanogpt/pull/266) by [@wilsoncwu](https://github.com/wilsoncwu) |\n\n## Method Summary\n\nRow 7 introduces Muon², implemented in the log as `MuonSq`. It keeps the broad row 1/3/6 optimizer split: hidden 2D transformer block matrices use a Muon-family optimizer, while embeddings, output head, gains, biases, and other non-2D parameters use auxiliary AdamW.\n\nThe new ingredient is Adam-style second-moment preconditioning before Newton-Schulz orthogonalization. The optimizer stores both Muon momentum and an elementwise second moment `v`. It updates `v` from squared gradients, forms the Nesterov-style Muon momentum update, divides that update elementwise by `sqrt(v) + eps`, and only then applies the same Newton-Schulz orthogonalization used by Muon.\n\nThe hidden settings are much more aggressive than prior plain Muon rows: LR `0.10`, WD `0.0125`, beta2 `0.95`, eps `1e-10`, momentum `0.95`, and the familiar 30 percent stable / 70 percent cooldown schedule. The log still uses 12 Newton-Schulz iterations, so this row's step-count gain is not from reducing iteration count. It is from changing the matrix that Newton-Schulz receives.\n\nThe allowed arXiv abstract frames Muon² as improving Muon by preconditioning the ill-conditioned momentum matrix before orthogonalization. The abstract claims this improves spectrum and directional alignment, and in broader experiments can reduce the number of Newton-Schulz iterations. The row log uses the quality side of that idea, not the fewer-iterations side.\n\n## Evidence Readout\n\n- Steps to `3.28`: `3325`.\n- Validation evidence: row reports `3.2752 (n=1)✓`; the log final is `3.27523`.\n- Seed count: one seed.\n- Date: 2026/04/29.\n- Caveats: one-seed evidence is fragile. The method looks strong on this seed, but row 6 showed that robust aggregate success and per-seed hit rate can differ. The PR page includes cross-reference text, but no linked or cross-referenced material was fetched or used.\n\n## Research Taste Diagnosis\n\nRow 7 is the clearest confirmation so far of the \"Muon plus adaptive magnitudes\" synthesis. Row 2's AdamW baseline made adaptive preconditioning feel scientifically important but not competitive by itself. Muon² keeps the Muon geometry and injects Adam-style second-moment information at the most natural point: before polar approximation.\n\nThe promising part is mechanism quality. Muon² changes the conditioning of the matrix passed into Newton-Schulz, not merely the scalar LR or radial policy. It attacks a different bottleneck from row 5/6. The fragile part is evidence: `n=1`.\n\nThe main taste update is that there are now three live branches:\n\n- Muon scalar/radial tuning: rows 3 and 6.\n- Hyperball/radius-constrained Muon: row 5.\n- Adam-preconditioned Muon directions: row 7.\n\nThese branches should be compared and combined carefully, not collapsed into one story too soon.",
