      "readmeDetail": "### 4. Compare NorMuonH Against Elementwise Muon²H\n\n- Rank: 4\n- Motivation: Row 7 preconditions before NS with full elementwise second moments; row 8 preconditions after NS with short-axis variance.\n- Mechanism: Implement matched hyperball variants using elementwise Muon², NorMuon short-axis preconditioning, and possibly both.\n- Expected benefit: Identify whether full elementwise, row/column, or placement-after-NS is the key adaptive ingredient.\n- Concrete experiment: Compare MuonH, Muon²H, NorMuonH, and pre-NS NorMuon-like variants with matched radii/schedules.\n- Expected failure mode: Full elementwise state may overfit or destabilize under hyperball projection.\n- Confidence: medium-high\n- Expected step gain: 25 to 100\n\nDetailed explanation:\n\nThis is the central mechanism ablation after row 8. It distinguishes row 7's adaptive path from row 8's adaptive path.",
      "rowContext": "## Method Summary\n\nRow 8 introduces NorMuonH, a synthesis of three revealed motifs:\n\n- Muon-style Newton-Schulz orthogonalized matrix directions.\n- NorMuon/Adafactor-style row/column variance preconditioning.\n- Hyperball Frobenius-norm preservation with per-module initialization radii.\n\nThe implementation is not the same as row 7 Muon². Row 7 preconditions the momentum matrix before Newton-Schulz. Row 8 first forms the Muon momentum update, applies Newton-Schulz, applies the usual Muon shape scaling, then computes a variance estimate over the short axis of the post-NS update and rescales the update with that row/column RMS estimate. Finally it applies the row 5-style hyperball step that preserves each hidden matrix's Frobenius norm.\n\nThe optimizer applies to all hidden 2D matrices: Q, K, V, MLP input, attention output projection, and MLP projection. It uses separate optimizer instances for QKV, MLP input, attention projection, and MLP projection, but the same LR and beta settings across those families.\n\nSettings:\n\n- Hidden matrix LR `0.018`.\n- Muon momentum `0.95`.\n- Variance beta2 `0.95`.\n- Epsilon `1e-10`.\n- Hidden cooldown fraction `1.0`.\n- Auxiliary cooldown fraction `0.4`.\n- No hidden weight decay, because hyperball projection controls hidden matrix norms.\n- Row 5-style per-module init stds: attention output projection about `0.026`, MLP projection about `0.031`, MLP input about `0.031`, QKV default.\n\nThe local log runs to `train_steps=3275`, but the row is credited at 3250 because the revealed seed is already below target at step `3250`, and the PR reports all 10 capture-full seeds first hit at step `3250`.\n\n## Research Taste Diagnosis\n\nRow 8 is a direct hit for branch synthesis. Row 5 made hyperball Muon robust at 3325. Row 7 made adaptive preconditioning look promising but one-seed fragile. Row 8 combines adaptive row/column normalization with hyperball geometry and gets robust 3250-step evidence.\n\nThe most promising part is the post-NS short-axis variance normalization. It is cheaper than full elementwise Muon² state and more geometrically aligned with matrix structure. It may balance neuron-level update energy while preserving Muon's spectral equalization.\n\nThe fragile part is attribution. Because the PR reports agent-assisted search and the method inherits row 5's init/schedule stack, I should not over-credit the preconditioner alone. Still, the row-level step improvement and n=10 evidence make this the strongest revealed direction so far.",
