      "readmeDetail": "### 3. Split u/w Targets and LR by Matrix Family\n\n- Rank: 3\n- Motivation: The same `0.35` relative update floor is applied to Q/K/V, attention projection, MLP expansion, and MLP projection matrices, even though their shapes and roles differ.\n- Mechanism: NorMuon-lite redistributes update energy by row or column; the u/w floor then sets global relative movement per matrix. Different matrix families may need different minimum relative step sizes or hidden LRs.\n- Expected benefit: Faster descent without changing optimizer state or adding new theory.\n- Concrete experiment: Start with family groups for Q/K, V, attention output projection, MLP input, and MLP projection. Sweep target floors and LR multipliers around the row 9 baseline, then validate finalists over multiple seeds.\n- Expected failure mode: The global floor already captures most of the benefit, and per-family tuning overfits one-seed screens.\n- Confidence: 0.63\n- Expected step gain: 50\n\nDetailed explanation: Earlier rows repeatedly exposed global settings where family-specific structure was plausible but untested. Row 9 makes the case stronger because relative update size depends on parameter norm, and parameter norms differ by family and initialization. A per-family target is a natural successor to per-module radii in the hyperball branch.",
