      "readmeDetail": "### 9. Co-Design Initialization With the Relative-Step Floor\n\n- Rank: 9\n- Motivation: The floor target is measured relative to `||w||_F`, so initial matrix norms directly affect early and mid-training behavior.\n- Mechanism: Larger initialized norms raise the floor's absolute update norm; smaller norms lower it. Unlike hyperball, the norms can then evolve, but the initial condition still shapes the trajectory.\n- Expected benefit: Better early stability and a lower final budget.\n- Concrete experiment: Compare row 9's zero-projection initialization, row 5-style per-module radius multipliers, and default nonzero projection initialization under the same floor target.\n- Expected failure mode: The floor quickly overwhelms initialization differences, or larger radii force too-large updates.\n- Confidence: 0.48\n- Expected step gain: 25\n\nDetailed explanation: Hyperball rows made initialization a radius policy. Row 9 loosens that constraint, but the floor still depends on parameter norm. That makes initialization less central than in MuonH, but still likely more important than in plain AdamW.",
