      "readmeDetail": "### 12. Combine Pre-NS and Post-NS Adaptive Normalization Under the Floor\n\n- Rank: 12\n- Motivation: Row 7 used pre-NS elementwise second moments, while rows 8 and 9 use post-NS row/column normalization. The u/w-floor gives a third radial stabilizer that may permit combining both.\n- Mechanism: Pre-NS preconditioning can improve the matrix that Newton-Schulz sees; post-NS normalization can redistribute energy across rows or columns; the floor can maintain relative step size after both.\n- Expected benefit: Better conditioned directions with controlled final scale.\n- Concrete experiment: Add a light pre-NS second-moment preconditioner to row 9's NorMuon-lite and compare against post-NS-only under matched floor/LR settings.\n- Expected failure mode: Double normalization erases useful signal or requires a much lower LR.\n- Confidence: 0.38\n- Expected step gain: 25\n\nDetailed explanation: This is lower-ranked because it adds complexity before the u/w-floor itself is mapped. But the revealed rows make pipeline placement a real axis, and row 9's relative-step control may reduce the risk of combining normalization stages.",
