      "readmeDetail": "### 2. Robustly Map the NorMuon LR/WD Surface Around `0.035`/`0.025`\n\n- Rank: 2\n- Motivation: Row 10 is a tuned NorMuon point, but only one LR/WD pair is revealed.\n- Mechanism: LR sets angular movement; WD sets radial shrinkage. Under Frobenius-renormalized NorMuon updates, these two knobs likely interact strongly.\n- Expected benefit: Better 3250 mean or a lower accepted endpoint.\n- Concrete experiment: Run a local grid around LR `0.030`, `0.035`, `0.040`, and WD `0.015`, `0.025`, `0.035`, using 3-seed screens and promoting top points to n=10 or n=20.\n- Expected failure mode: The current point is already near a ridge, and improvements are smaller than seed noise.\n- Confidence: 0.70\n- Expected step gain: 50\n\nDetailed explanation: Rows 3, 6, and 10 all reward scalar optimizer tuning. The right next step is not a more ornate method; it is a robust map of the local NorMuon LR/WD surface with the accepted evidence standard in mind.",
      "rowContext": "## Method Summary\n\nRow 10 is a plain NorMuon hidden-matrix optimizer with auxiliary AdamW for the non-hidden-matrix parameters. It is \"plain\" relative to the recent frontier because it does not use the row 8 hyperball projection and does not use the row 9 u/w-floor. Instead, it uses NorMuon row/column variance normalization plus actual decoupled hidden weight decay.\n\nThe hidden update path is:\n\n1. Maintain a Muon-style momentum buffer.\n2. Form a Nesterov-style matrix update.\n3. Apply 12 Newton-Schulz iterations to approximate the polar factor.\n4. Apply the usual Muon shape scaling.\n5. Compute a row or column second-moment EMA over the post-NS update, choosing the axis based on whether the matrix is tall or wide.\n6. Divide the update by `sqrt(second_momentum)`.\n7. Renormalize the update back to its pre-normalization Frobenius norm.\n8. Apply decoupled weight decay to the parameter.\n9. Add the NorMuon update with hidden LR `0.035`.\n\nAuxiliary AdamW keeps the familiar groups: embedding LR `0.3`, output head LR `1/320`, scalar/vector LR `0.01`, betas `(0.8, 0.95)`, eps `1e-10`, and no auxiliary weight decay.\n\nThe training loop sets `train_steps = 3300`, but the leaderboard row accepts the method at step 3250: \"end 50 steps early.\" This matters because the schedule is computed against 3300. At step 3250, the LR has not fully decayed to zero; it is a small but nonzero fraction of the initial LR.\n\nInitialization is explicit: projection weights are zeroed, embedding weights use default normal initialization, other hidden weights use `normal_(std=sqrt(0.33 / fan_in))`, biases are zeroed, and gains are initialized to one.\n\n## Research Taste Diagnosis\n\nThe main taste lesson is that the NorMuon branch is robust without needing the latest radial gadget. Row 10 is not a new mechanism relative to rows 8 and 9; it is a cleaner, statistically stronger point in the same design space. That is valuable. It makes NorMuon itself less fragile as a human direction and moves the research question from \"does row/column normalization work?\" to \"which radial policy and schedule horizon should surround it?\"\n\nThe local 10-trial evidence at 3250 is especially instructive. It has mean `3.27879`, but with n=10 the margin is small. One run is above `3.28`. The row becomes accepted at n=20 with leaderboard mean `3.2789`. This is a concrete example of robust evidence as a competitive lever: more seeds can turn a near-miss into a passing row if the mean is real and variance is small.\n\nThe schedule-horizon detail is the most promising hidden knob. The method is accepted at 3250 while using `train_steps=3300` internally. That means endpoint and schedule are not the same variable. If future experiments only set `train_steps` equal to the claimed endpoint, they may miss this effect.",
