      "readmeDetail": "## Revealed Row\n\n`| 11 | 3225(!) | 3.2785 (n=16)✓ | Setup from #9 plus Contra-Muon technique (note: p-value vs. #9 is p=0.69) | 2026/05/01 | log: results/20260501_contra_muon/08cd60f9-99e2-4e28-b1ac-19136dd42a05.txt | PR: https://github.com/KellerJordan/modded-nanogpt/pull/275 by @nilin |`\n\n## Method Summary\n\nRow 11 builds directly on the row 9 Skylight setup: NorMuon-lite row/column variance normalization, Frobenius renormalization, u/w-floor with target `0.35`, hidden LR `0.0375`, and no effective hidden weight decay despite the logged `muon_weight_decay=0.025` parameter. The new ingredient is Contra-Muon.\n\nContra-Muon modifies the Muon Newton-Schulz update by subtracting a fraction of the operator-normalized momentum-gradient direction. In the revealed code, `CONTRA_MUON = 0.4`, so the subtractive component is `0.2 * normalized_grad`.\n\nThe pipeline is:\n\n1. Update the momentum buffer and form the usual Nesterov-style update.\n2. Estimate the operator norm of that momentum update with five power-iteration steps and divide by it.\n3. Apply Newton-Schulz to get the Muon polar-style update.\n4. Save the Frobenius norm of that Muon update.\n5. Subtract `CONTRA_MUON / 2` times the operator-normalized momentum update.\n6. Renormalize back to the saved Frobenius norm.\n7. Apply the usual Muon shape scaling.\n8. Apply NorMuon-lite row/column variance normalization and Frobenius renormalization.\n9. Apply the row 9 u/w-floor.\n10. Take the hidden update with LR `0.0375`.\n\nThe local log uses `train_steps = 3225` and extra validations at 3150, 3175, 3200, and 3225. The local log is seed 9. The PR reports n=16 non-cherry-picked seeds 1-16.\n\n## Evidence Readout\n\n- Steps to `3.28`: `3225`.\n- Validation evidence: leaderboard `3.2785 (n=16)`.\n- Seed count: PR reports 16 non-cherry-picked seeds 1-16. The local allowed log is seed 9.\n- Date: `2026/05/01`.\n- Caveats:\n  - The leaderboard row explicitly notes p-value versus row 9 is `p=0.69`, so row 11 should not be interpreted as statistically proving superiority over row 9.\n  - The PR's threshold evidence at 3225 is strong, but the 3200 mean does not pass the track statistic with n=16.\n  - The PR reports a shared-step comparison at 3125 against the row 9 ancestor, but direct leaderboard superiority remains statistically weak per the row note.\n  - No existing hyperparameters were changed relative to row 9 except the Contra-Muon addition.\n\nLocal seed 9 trajectory near the end:\n\n```text\n3125: 3.28489\n3150: 3.28237\n3175: 3.28033\n3200: 3.27880\n3225: 3.27807\n```\n\nPR seed table summary:\n\n```text\n3200 mean: 3.27929188\n3225 mean: 3.27854062\nbest 3225 value shown: 3.27626\nworst 3225 value shown: 3.28000\n```\n\n## Research Taste Diagnosis\n\nContra-Muon is the first revealed row that directly reopens the spectral-transform question around Muon. Rows 8 through 10 mostly changed row/column allocation or radial policy. Row 11 changes what \"orthogonalized direction\" means by damping the largest singular modes relative to smaller ones.\n\nThe method is appealing because it is a small, targeted modification: no LR, floor, or schedule retune is needed to produce a row-level gain. That makes the mechanism legible. But the statistical caveat is equally important. The row passes the threshold at 3225; it does not convincingly beat row 9 head-to-head.\n\nThe 3200 mean is tantalizing. It is below 3.28, but not enough under the benchmark statistic with n=16. If the mean were stable, roughly doubling the seed count would be near the threshold for a 3200 claim, but the better research move is probably to tune the Contra coefficient or schedule for a small mean improvement before spending many more seeds.",
