      "readmeDetail": "### 9. Retune Initialization For Plain Muon+WD\n\n- Rank: 9\n- Motivation: Row 12 uses row 10-style explicit initialization but not NorMuon.\n- Mechanism: Initial norms and zero projection choices interact with high LR and WD.\n- Expected benefit: Improve early stability and late margin.\n- Concrete experiment: Compare row 12 init with row 5-style per-module radii and default nonzero projection init.\n- Expected failure mode: Plain Muon+WD quickly washes out initialization differences.\n- Confidence: 0.36\n- Expected step gain: 15\n\nDetailed explanation: Initialization is less central than in hyperball rows, but still part of the recipe.",
      "rowContext": "## Method Summary\n\nRow 12 returns to plain Muon with auxiliary AdamW. It does not use NorMuon row/column variance normalization, hyperball projection, u/w-floor, Muon² preconditioning, or Contra-Muon. The hidden 2D transformer block matrices use Muon with LR `0.035`, weight decay `0.025`, momentum `0.95`, Nesterov-style update, 12 Newton-Schulz iterations, and shape scaling. The auxiliary parameter groups use AdamW for embeddings, output head, gains, biases, and other non-2D parameters.\n\nThe method follows row 10's scalar settings but applies them to plain Muon rather than NorMuon: hidden LR `0.035` and hidden WD `0.025`. It also follows the \"end early\" pattern: the script sets `train_steps = 3350`, but the leaderboard accepts the result at step `3325`, 25 steps before the configured schedule horizon.\n\nInitialization also follows the explicit default-style pattern from row 10: projection weights are zeroed, embeddings are normal initialized, other hidden weights use `normal_(std=sqrt(0.33 / fan_in))`, biases are zeroed, and gains are set to one.\n\n## Research Taste Diagnosis\n\nRow 12 is a baseline-quality row in the best sense. It does not introduce a shiny new optimizer mechanism. It asks whether plain Muon, pushed to a higher LR and paired with strong WD plus an end-early schedule horizon, can still compete. The answer is yes enough to pass at 3325, though not enough to beat the 3225/3250 frontier.\n\nThe row also strengthens the schedule-horizon lesson. Row 10 used a 3300 horizon and accepted at 3250. Row 12 uses a 3350 horizon and accepts at 3325. This starts to look like a general recipe: tune the cooldown endpoint slightly beyond the leaderboard claim so the model still learns during the final reported validation.\n\nThe caveat is that the margin is thin. At step 3300 the mean is still above target and only 6/20 trials pass; by 3325 the mean clears the aggregate statistic. A few dozen steps of late cooldown matter a lot.",
