      "readmeDetail": "3. **Tune endpoint alignment to the outer interval.** Test endpoints that are exact multiples of `H` and endpoints that land between outer steps. If the final outer step matters, endpoint choice is now a discrete optimizer hyperparameter.",
      "rowContext": "## Method Summary\n\nRow 13 takes the row 8 NorMuonH stack and adds a second optimizer operating outside the ordinary inner optimization loop. The inner stack remains:\n\n- auxiliary AdamW for embeddings, output head, gains, biases, and other non-hidden-matrix parameters;\n- NorMuonH for hidden 2D block weights;\n- Muon Newton-Schulz direction, post-NS short-axis row/column variance normalization, and fixed-Frobenius hyperball projection;\n- row 8-style per-module initialization radii;\n- hidden cooldown fraction `1.0` and auxiliary cooldown fraction `0.4`.\n\nThe new ingredient is `NesterovOuterOptimizer`, which wraps every trainable parameter. It stores a snapshot of all parameters, lets the inner optimizers run for `H=30` inner steps, then computes a pseudogradient\n\n```text\ndelta = snapshot - current_params\n```\n\nand applies an outer Nesterov-style SGD update with `outer_lr=0.7` and `outer_momentum=0.5`. The implementation keeps one outer momentum buffer per trainable parameter and one snapshot tensor per trainable parameter. After each outer step, it refreshes the snapshots to the newly updated parameters.\n\nThe local log sets `train_steps=3210`, which is exactly `107 * 30`, so the final validation occurs immediately after a full number of outer synchronizations. This is not the same as the row 10/12 schedule-horizon trick: here the claimed endpoint and the configured train horizon are the same, but they are aligned to the outer optimizer interval.",
