      "readmeDetail": "## Revealed Row\n\n| # | Steps to 3.28 | Evidence | Description | Date | Log | Contributors |\n| - | - | - | - | - | - | - |\n| 18 | 3225 | 3.2776 (n=9) | PMuon: Muon + bilateral streaming covariance power preconditioning, lr=.035 wd=.025 gamma=.3 beta=.95 | 2026/05/07 | `results/20260507_pmuon/54fc0541-7a62-4772-a8f8-d3a46ad10dba.txt` | PR #285 by `@zzp1012` |\n\n## Method Summary\n\nPMuon, or Preconditioned Muon, changes the metric in which Muon performs its polar equalization. Standard Muon takes the momentum-like matrix `M` and applies:\n\n```text\npolar(M)\n```\n\nPMuon first applies bilateral covariance power preconditioning:\n\n```text\npolar(L^{-gamma} M R^{-gamma})\n```\n\nwhere:\n\n- `R` is a streaming right/column gradient covariance estimate, roughly `G^T G`;\n- `L` is a streaming left/row gradient covariance estimate, roughly `G G^T`;\n- `gamma=0.3` controls the power-preconditioning strength;\n- `beta=0.95` controls the streaming covariance decay.\n\nThe intuition is different from row 17 Aurora. Aurora changes the polar operator by balancing leverage for rectangular matrices. PMuon changes the metric before the polar step using gradient covariance on both sides. It suppresses high-variance directions and relatively amplifies low-variance directions, then asks Muon to equalize singular modes in that corrected metric.",
