      "readmeDetail": "## Revealed Row\n\n| Row | Step | Validation | Method | Date | Evidence | Contributor |\n| - | -: | - | - | - | - | - |\n| 25 | 3040 | 3.2781 (n=5) | Setup from #19 KL-SOAP-H, plus power LR decay over a 3125-step horizon with nonzero Adam/KL-SOAP LR floors | 2026/05/11 | `results/20260511_klsoap_h_lr_power_decay/01906576-8b3d-4bd2-a73f-23997f602ec1.txt`, PR 293 | @chenchenygu |\n\n## Method Summary\n\nRow 25 is a schedule improvement on the row 19 KL-SOAP-H branch. It does not introduce a new hidden optimizer. The hidden matrices still use KL-SOAP-H: SOAP-like structured adaptive preconditioning in a learned left/right basis, Adam-like first and second moments in that basis, and a hyperball-style scale-invariant update that returns each hidden matrix to its previous Frobenius norm.\n\nThe new ingredient is the LR schedule:\n\n- `train_steps = 3040`;\n- `schedule_steps = 3125`;\n- `lr_power = 1.5`;\n- AdamW auxiliary groups use `cooldown_frac = 0.4` and `lr_floor = 0.04`;\n- KL-SOAP-H hidden groups use `cooldown_frac = 1.0` and `lr_floor = 0.017`;\n- both groups use the same power-law decay formula.\n\nThe PR frames this as a per-optimizer improvement for the KL-SOAP-H line, not a new global step-count record. That is the right interpretation: the scientific value is that a structured-adaptive/hyperball branch from row 19 becomes much faster through schedule shape, endpoint-horizon separation, and nonzero LR floors.",
      "sourcePath": "outputs/row_25/README.md"
