      "readmeDetail": "## Revealed Row\n\n| Row | Step | Validation | Method | Date | Evidence | Contributors |\n| - | -: | - | - | - | - | - |\n| 26 | 3090 | 3.2785 (n=10) | SinkSOAP: Gram-Sinkhorn SOAP-style preconditioning with NorMuon postconditioner, lr=0.04 wd=0.025, no power LR schedule | 2026/05/14 | `results/20260514_sinksoap/d0155dd0-f77d-48a9-8eb4-453f894b9476.txt`, PR 298 | @lliu606, @zhenghaoxu-gatech |\n\n## Method Summary\n\nRow 26 introduces SinkSOAP, a SOAP-space optimizer that deliberately avoids SOAP's usual rotated-space second-moment preconditioner. The method keeps the useful idea of rotating a matrix update into left/right Gram eigenspaces, but then applies Sinkhorn-style row/column energy balancing directly to the rotated Nesterov momentum.\n\nThe hidden 2D block matrices use SinkSOAP. Auxiliary parameters use the familiar AdamW split for embeddings, output head, and scalar/vector parameters. The method is not a Muon-family stack: the PR states that it is mostly an independent optimizer and is not mixed with most previous methods, including Muon. The inherited component is the NorMuon-style size-dependent normalization idea for non-square matrices.",
