      "readmeDetail": "## Revealed Row\n\n`| 29 | 2990(!) | 3.2787 (n=11)✓ | Setup from #20, plus radial brake: dampens outward radial updates before the u/w floor | 2026/05/11 | [log](results/20260511_dampen_radial_gradient_component/00882c75-914d-4340-8e0b-dcffcb18b73d.txt) | [PR](https://github.com/KellerJordan/modded-nanogpt/pull/294) by [@nilin](https://github.com/nilin) |`\n\n## Method Summary\n\nRow 29 starts from the row 20-style stack: scheduled Contra-Muon into normal Muon into late Soft-Muon, V/MLP SOAP coverage, PowerCool-style late learning-rate schedule, and a u/w floor with target `0.3825`. The new ingredient is a \"radial brake\" inserted just before the u/w floor.\n\nFor each hidden matrix, the optimizer decomposes the proposed update into a component parallel to the current parameter matrix and a tangential component. Because the actual parameter update is `p.add_(update, alpha=-lr)`, an update coefficient with `coeff < 0` means the step would move outward, increasing the matrix radius. Row 29 scales that outward radial component by `0.5`, while preserving inward radial movement with scale `1.0`.\n\nAfter the radial brake, the existing u/w floor still applies. If `||update||_F / ||weight||_F` is below `0.3825`, the entire update is scaled up to that floor. The method then computes the intended first-order radius change from the damped radial component, takes the update step, and rescales the parameter back to the radius implied by that intended radial change. This last correction removes the second-order radius growth caused by tangential motion.\n\n## Evidence Readout\n\n- Steps to `3.28`: accepted at `2990`.\n- Validation evidence: leaderboard row `3.2787 (n=11)`; PR body reports mean `3.27866818` over seeds `0` through `10`.\n- Seed count: `11` non-cherry-picked seed logfiles in the PR report.\n- Date: `2026/05/11`.\n- Caveats: the local log is one representative seed, not the aggregate. The method builds on many inherited row 20 ingredients, so the marginal effect of radial brake needs ablation. The representative seed continues improving after 2990, reaching `3.27633` by step `3020`, so the accepted row does not prove 2990 is the absolute lower boundary.\n\n## Research Taste Diagnosis\n\nThe promising part is the precision of the radial intervention. Row 29 does not simply add more decay or project onto a fixed sphere. It says outward and inward radial motion have different value, and it also accounts for the second-order norm effect of tangent updates. That is a much cleaner optimizer primitive than another scalar weight-decay sweep.\n\nThe fragile part is interaction with the u/w floor. Because the floor scales the whole update after radial damping, it can partially re-amplify the damped radial component. The method may work because it changes the direction mix enough before floor activation, but the order of operations is now a core hyperparameter.\n\nThe undertuned surface is large: outward scale, inward scale, u/w target, floor placement, post-step correction, family-specific radial policy, and phase-specific radial policy. The row is a strong proof of taste, not the end of the radial-control search.",
