      "readmeDetail": "### 2. Ablate Brake, Floor, And Radius Correction Separately\n\n- Rank: 2\n- Motivation: Row 29 combines three radial operations: directional damping, u/w floor scaling, and post-step radius correction.\n- Mechanism: Compare no brake, brake only, radius correction only, u/w floor only, brake plus floor, brake plus correction, and all three.\n- Expected benefit: Attribute the gain and prevent accidental over-crediting of the new brake when the correction or floor ordering may be the real driver.\n- Concrete experiment: Use identical seeds around `2990` and log validation plus per-matrix radius drift for each ablation.\n- Expected failure mode: Individual components may look weak alone because their gain is an interaction.\n- Confidence: `0.71`\n- Expected step gain: `0` to `15`\n\nDetailed explanation: The radius correction is not cosmetic. Tangent updates can grow norms second-order, and row 29 actively removes that growth. A good ablation could reveal that radius correction is as important as outward damping.",
