      "readmeDetail": "### 3. Move The Radial Brake Relative To The u/w Floor\n\n- Rank: 3\n- Motivation: The current row applies radial damping before the u/w floor, and the floor then scales the entire update.\n- Mechanism: Test brake-before-floor, floor-before-brake, and a split rule where the floor scales only the tangential component while preserving the braked radial component.\n- Expected benefit: Preserve the target relative step size without undoing the radial-safety intervention.\n- Concrete experiment: Reuse row 29 constants and compare endpoint means at `2980`, `2990`, and `3000`.\n- Expected failure mode: Floor-after-brake may be necessary because the optimizer needs a minimum full-update magnitude, not just angular motion.\n- Confidence: `0.68`\n- Expected step gain: `5` to `15`\n\nDetailed explanation: If the u/w floor mostly activates late, this ordering may dominate the accepted endpoint. A tangent-only floor is an especially natural next mechanism because row 29 already decomposes radial and tangential motion.",
