      "readmeDetail": "### 5. Schedule The Radial Brake Across Spectral Phases\n\n- Rank: 5\n- Motivation: Row 29 is built on a phase-scheduled spectral stack, but the radial brake is static.\n- Mechanism: Use weaker braking during early Contra-Muon, moderate braking during normal Muon, and stronger outward braking during late Soft-Muon and cooldown.\n- Expected benefit: Avoid slowing early representation formation while preventing late u/w-floor-driven radius expansion near the claim endpoint.\n- Concrete experiment: Couple outward scale to the known phase boundaries: `1.0` early, linearly decay to `0.5`, then optionally to `0.25` after the Soft-Muon transition.\n- Expected failure mode: A dynamic brake may introduce too many interacting schedules and lose the simplicity that made row 29 robust.\n- Confidence: `0.61`\n- Expected step gain: `5` to `15`\n\nDetailed explanation: Spectral transfer and radial policy are separable but not independent. When Soft-Muon changes the singular-value map late, the radial composition of the update may also need to change.",
