      "readmeDetail": "### 9. Combine Matrix-Level Brake With Row-Level Gain Control\n\n- Rank: 9\n- Motivation: Prior row-norm work suggests matrix-wide radius is not the only useful norm coordinate.\n- Mechanism: Apply the radial brake at matrix level, then use row-level gain or V-norm targets to control angular displacement inside each matrix.\n- Expected benefit: Prevent global radius expansion while giving rows/families different effective angular step sizes.\n- Concrete experiment: Use the row 29 stack and replace the global u/w floor with a row-level target for MLP projection only, keeping global brake active.\n- Expected failure mode: Too much norm control may over-constrain updates and reduce useful exploration.\n- Confidence: `0.43`\n- Expected step gain: `5` to `20`\n\nDetailed explanation: Row 29 says radial and tangential should be separated. Row-level gain control asks whether tangential motion also needs local structure, especially in rectangular matrices.",
