      "readmeDetail": "### 2. Sweep Aurora Scope: `mlp.proj` Only, `mlp.fc` Only, Both, Neither\n\n- Rank: 2\n- Motivation: The row claims Aurora helps wide `mlp.proj` but fights tall `mlp.fc`.\n- Mechanism: Apply Aurora by matrix family and shape, while keeping the pruned row 30 stack fixed.\n- Expected benefit: Confirm whether shape-specific scope is the core discovery and whether some layers or families deserve exceptions.\n- Concrete experiment: Test no Aurora, `mlp.proj` only, `mlp.fc` only, both MLP matrices, and per-depth subsets of `mlp.proj`.\n- Expected failure mode: `mlp.fc` may only fail under the current depth-scaled init and might look better after init retuning.\n- Confidence: `0.73`\n- Expected step gain: `5` to `20`\n\nDetailed explanation: Row 30's strongest claim is not just \"Aurora works\"; it is \"Aurora belongs on wide projection matrices.\" That scope should be tested before adding more optimizer machinery.",
      "rowContext": "## Method Summary\n\nRow 30 starts from the row 29 radial-brake stack but prunes and reshapes it. The key new ingredient is Aurora row-balanced polar applied only to the wide MLP projection matrices, `mlp.proj.weight`, whose shape is `768 x 3072`. All square attention matrices and tall `mlp.fc.weight` matrices continue through the ordinary Muon-style Newton-Schulz polar path.\n\nFor originally wide matrices, the update is transposed, diagonally row-rescaled, run through the Newton-Schulz polar procedure, and then the row rescaling is updated. This repeats for `_AURORA_K = 3` outer iterations with `_AURORA_BETA = 0.25` and `_AURORA_EPS = 1e-7`. The PR says Aurora is restricted to wide `mlp.proj` because the row-uniform constraint fights the depth-scaled `mlp.fc` initialization on tall matrices.\n\nThe row also removes two inherited ingredients from the row 20/29 lineage:\n\n- Soft-Muon is disabled by setting `SOFT_MUON_CEIL = 0.00`, so `soft_blend_for_step` always returns zero even though the soft update is still computed.\n- NorMuon-lite is disabled by setting `NOR_BETA2 = 1.0`. The second-moment buffer no longer updates, and after the final Frobenius renormalization the variance-scaling path is effectively neutral.\n\nThe Contra-Muon ramp is extended: `CONTRA_TO_NORMAL_END_STEP` moves from the row 29-era `2000` to `2500`, so Contra influence decays more slowly. The row also uses a Muon momentum schedule from prior speedrun lineage: `mu` warms from `0.85` to `0.95` over the first `300` steps, stays high through most training, then cools from `0.95` to `0.85` over the final `100` steps.\n\nThe row keeps the radial brake from row 29: outward radial update scale `0.5`, inward scale `1.0`, u/w floor target `0.3825`, and post-step radius correction. MLP plus V SOAP remain enabled. The local log also includes depth-scaled `mlp.fc` initialization with alpha `0.30` and a CGI Rademacher norm-gain split with alpha `0.14`.\n\n## Research Taste Diagnosis\n\nThe promising part is shape-specific optimizer surgery. Row 30 does not say \"Aurora everywhere\"; it says `mlp.proj` is the right place for row-balanced polar, and `mlp.fc` is the wrong place under the current initialization. That is much more plausible than a uniform wrapper.\n\nThe second promising part is subtractive taste. Soft-Muon and NorMuon-lite were previously valuable-looking ingredients, but row 30 removes them because the current stack suggests negative marginal value. This is a strong human taste pattern: once a new primitive changes geometry, re-test which old primitives are now redundant or harmful.\n\nThe fragile part is bundling. The accepted endpoint improves from row 29, but Aurora, phase pruning, momentum scheduling, and initialization changes all move together. The row is excellent as a frontier recipe and hypothesis generator, but not yet a clean causal proof of Aurora-on-proj.",
