      "readmeDetail": "### 9. Tune Muown LR, Direction Scale, And Momentum Jointly\n\n- Rank: 9\n- Motivation: Row 31 uses `LR_MUOWN=0.0045`, direction scale `0.2 * sqrt(max(m,n))`, and momentum `0.946`.\n- Mechanism: Search the local angular step-size surface under Contra and NorMuon.\n- Expected benefit: Recover speed after changing direction geometry.\n- Concrete experiment: Sweep LR around `0.0045`, direction scale multipliers around `0.2`, and momentum in `{0.93,0.946,0.96}`.\n- Expected failure mode: Gains may be dominated by V-norm scheduling rather than scalar angular step size.\n- Confidence: `0.48`\n- Expected step gain: `0` to `15`\n\nDetailed explanation: Once the direction update changes, the old Muown LR/momentum surface may no longer be optimal.",
      "rowContext": "## Method Summary\n\nRow 31 returns to the row 23 Muown branch and ports two Muon-family mechanisms into it: NorMuon-lite and Contra-Muon. It also uses a power-law LR cooldown.\n\nMuown parameterizes each hidden matrix row into a gain `g` and an internal direction `v`. The optimizer computes gradients for the row gain and the normalized direction separately. Direction gradients receive Muon-style momentum, a Polar Express long Newton-Schulz polar update, optional Contra-Muon correction, optional NorMuon-lite variance renormalization, and then a scheduled V-norm target. Row gains are updated with Adam-style first and second moments.\n\nThe revealed settings are:\n\n- `LR_MUOWN = 0.0045`\n- `MUOWN_MOMENTUM = 0.946`\n- `CONTRA_MUON = 0.65`\n- `CONTRA_TO_NORMAL_END_STEP = 1925`\n- `NOR_MUON = True`\n- `NOR_MUON_BETA2 = 0.80`\n- `V_NORM_TARGET_SCALE = 2.496`\n- `V_NORM_SCHEDULE_STEPS = 3005`\n- `V_NORM_SCHEDULE_POWER = 0.9`\n- `LR_SCHEDULE_STEPS = 3045`\n- `LR_POWER = 0.9`\n- `train_steps = 3000`\n\nFamily-specific V-norm multipliers are:\n\n```text\nattn.q.weight: 1.0\nattn.k.weight: 1.0\nattn.v.weight: 1.0\nattn.proj.weight: 1.5\nmlp.fc.weight: 1.5\nmlp.proj.weight: 3.33333333333\n```\n\nThe auxiliary AdamW path uses `LR_EMBED=0.6`, `LR_HEAD=0.009375`, and `LR_1D=0.03`.\n\n## Research Taste Diagnosis\n\nThe promising part is that Muown remains composable. Row-level gain/direction control does not make Contra or NorMuon obsolete; it creates a new substrate for them. This supports the idea that row-norm control is not an isolated trick but a branch that can absorb Muon-family direction improvements.\n\nThe fragile part is causal attribution. Contra, NorMuon-lite, V-norm target scale, family multipliers, LR schedule, and LR values all moved together relative to the original row 23 memory. A clean 2x2 Contra/NorMuon ablation is mandatory before crediting either mechanism.\n\nThe benchmark-specific caveat is that row 31 is not the fastest revealed endpoint. Its research value is branch improvement and compositional evidence: row-level optimizers can inherit spectral and postconditioning ideas from the Muon family.",
