      "readmeDetail": "### 5. Rank Threshold And Epsilon Policy For Pseudoinverse Roots\n\n- Rank: 5\n- Motivation: `shampoo_epsilon=0` plus pseudoinverse root is a bold rank-handling choice.\n- Mechanism: The preconditioner may need to ignore null or tiny eigen-directions early, then gradually trust more directions as statistics fill in.\n- Expected benefit: Improve stability and reduce early wasted motion without blunting useful curvature.\n- Concrete experiment: Sweep pseudoinverse tolerance/rank cutoff if exposed by the package; otherwise compare epsilon `0`, `1e-12`, `1e-8`, and small scheduled floors.\n- Expected failure mode: The package default pseudoinverse policy is already optimal, or exposed epsilon knobs do not affect the actual rank threshold.\n- Confidence: 0.58\n- Expected step gain: 20\n\nDetailed explanation: The row likely works partly because it handles rank deficiency cleanly. But a fixed rank policy may be wrong across training phases: early projections are zero and late matrices are richer.",
