      "readmeDetail": "### 9. Replace Strong WD With Hyperball Or Trust-Region Radial Control\n\n- Rank: 9\n- Motivation: Row 35 uses decoupled WD `0.1`, much stronger than most Muon-family hidden WD values.\n- Mechanism: WD is acting as radial control for Shampoo-preconditioned hidden matrices; Hyperball or trust-region clipping could control radius more directly.\n- Expected benefit: Stabilize Shampoo directions while reducing over-decay or family-mismatched radial pressure.\n- Concrete experiment: Compare WD `0.1` against Hyperball radius preservation, trust-region clipping plus WD, and family-specific WD values.\n- Expected failure mode: Strong decoupled WD is exactly what keeps Shampoo viable, and projection/clipping slows the already-slow branch.\n- Confidence: 0.46\n- Expected step gain: 20\n\nDetailed explanation: Previous rows repeatedly show radial policy is the optimizer. Shampoo should be judged under the same radial-policy discipline as Muon, SOAP, PSGD, and KL-SOAP-H.",
      "rowContext": "## Method Summary\n\nRow 35 is a serious Shampoo-family control rather than a new fast frontier row. It keeps the standard GPT model, data loader, initialization, auxiliary AdamW split, and stable-then-linear cooldown schedule. The hidden 2D block matrices are optimized by `DistributedShampoo`; embeddings, output head, gains, biases, and other non-2D parameters stay on auxiliary AdamW.\n\nThe hidden optimizer is configured as One-Sided Shampoo in the row text. In the visible script, the `DistributedShampoo` call uses:\n\n- hidden LR `0.01`;\n- betas `(0.9, 0.9)`;\n- decoupled hidden weight decay `0.1`;\n- `epsilon=0.0`;\n- `max_preconditioner_dim=8192`;\n- `precondition_frequency=1`;\n- `start_preconditioning_step=-1`;\n- root-inverse Shampoo preconditioner with eigendecomposition and `PseudoInverseConfig`;\n- Adam grafting with beta2 `0.9` and epsilon `1e-15`;\n- DDP distributed config that communicates parameters across all 8 H200 GPUs.\n\nAuxiliary AdamW is the familiar split: embedding LR `0.3`, output head LR `1/320`, scalar/vector LR `0.01`, betas `(0.8, 0.95)`, epsilon `1e-10`, no weight decay, and fused AdamW. The learning-rate schedule is the older stable-plus-linear cooldown with `cooldown_frac=0.7` and `train_steps=3375`; unlike several recent rows, the accepted endpoint is also the schedule endpoint.\n\n## Research Taste Diagnosis\n\nThe promising part is not the absolute step count. It is that a structured second-order method can be made to cross the target with a coherent recipe and reasonable per-step time. That matters because weak baseline rows can create false confidence in Muon-family or SOAP-family claims. Row 35 says the Shampoo baseline still has knobs worth respecting.\n\nThe fragile part is attribution. The row description names One-Sided Shampoo, but the visible script also changes pseudoinverse root stability, removes Shampoo epsilon, uses tiny Adam graft epsilon, applies every-step preconditioning, and uses strong decoupled weight decay. Any one of those could be essential, harmful, or merely inherited from a good package default.\n\nThe most actionable taste lesson is to treat Shampoo as a family of choices rather than a monolith: side choice, root computation, rank handling, grafting, epsilon floors, decay, precondition frequency, schedule, and matrix-family scope.",
