      "readmeDetail": "### 1. Factorial Aux AdamW Versus Muon Retune Ablation\n\n- Rank: 1\n- Motivation: Row 36 is bundled, and causal credit matters.\n- Mechanism: Separate auxiliary LR/WD changes from hidden Muon LR/WD changes and from shorter endpoint.\n- Expected benefit: Identify whether the new baseline gain comes from auxiliary parameters, hidden radial policy, or interaction.\n- Concrete experiment: Run a 2x2x2 ladder: old versus tuned auxiliary AdamW, old versus tuned Muon LR/WD, and 3250 versus 3350 train_steps, on shared seeds.\n- Expected failure mode: The gain is distributed across small interactions, so individual ablations look weak.\n- Confidence: 0.82\n- Expected step gain: 0\n\nDetailed explanation: This is the highest-value next step because row 36 is a research-taste correction. The result is only useful if it tells us which old assumptions were stale.",
      "rowContext": "## Method Summary\n\nRow 36 is a tuned plain-baseline row: standard Muon on hidden 2D block matrices plus auxiliary AdamW on embeddings, output head, gains, biases, and other non-2D parameters. There is no NorMuon, Contra, SOAP, Hyperball, Muown, SODA, RRE, Shampoo, or other extra optimizer mechanism in the visible script.\n\nThe visible Muon update is the original-style recipe:\n\n- momentum `mu=0.95`;\n- Nesterov-style update;\n- 12 Newton-Schulz iterations with coefficients `(2, -1.5, 0.5)`;\n- shape scaling by `sqrt(max(1, rows / cols))`;\n- decoupled hidden weight decay before the Muon step.\n\nThe row changes the scalar recipe relative to the PR's stated baseline:\n\n- `train_steps`: `3350 -> 3250`;\n- auxiliary AdamW embedding LR: `0.3 -> 0.7`;\n- auxiliary AdamW output projection LR: `1/320 -> 0.004`;\n- auxiliary AdamW 1D/scalar/vector LR: `0.01 -> 0.015`;\n- auxiliary AdamW weight decay: `0 -> 0.001`;\n- hidden Muon LR: `0.035 -> 0.025`;\n- hidden Muon weight decay: `0.025 -> 0.05`.\n\nThe schedule is the older shared stable-then-linear cooldown with `cooldown_frac=0.7` and `train_steps=3250`. Unlike some prior schedule-horizon rows, the claimed endpoint equals the training/schedule endpoint.\n\nInitialization is the explicit default-style scheme: projection weights zeroed, embeddings normal initialized, other hidden weights normal with std `sqrt(0.33 / fan_in)`, biases zeroed, and gains set to one.\n\n## Research Taste Diagnosis\n\nWhat seems promising is the simplicity. Plain Muon was not exhausted. The optimizer split from row 1 is still a design surface, and row 36 shows that tuning the non-hidden-matrix path can matter as much as changing the hidden matrix optimizer.\n\nWhat seems fragile is causal attribution. If the auxiliary LRs alone caused most of the gain, then many prior rows need re-evaluation under tuned aux settings. If hidden WD `0.05` caused most of the gain, then the radial-policy bucket gets another strong point. If the interaction matters, then single-axis ablations will be misleading.\n\nThe row also changes how to think about \"baseline\". A baseline is not just the old Muon script; it is the best known Muon plus auxiliary AdamW recipe under the current evidence standard. Future exotic optimizer claims should compare against this tuned baseline, not against stale auxiliary settings.",
      "sourcePath": "outputs/row_36/ideas.json"
